<h1>Example 1</h1>

<section>
	<p class="example-intro">The simplest way to fix comma splices is to divide the two independent clauses into seperate sentences. The following examples present sentences with comma splices, and then corrects them by splitting them into seperate sentences. </p>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The nurse left his job at the hospital, he took a job in a private practice. <span class="red">COMMA SPLICE!</span></h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">Here we see a comma splice. The two independent clauses, "the nurse left his job at the hospital" and "he took a job in a private practice", are connected with nothing but a comma.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The nurse left his job at the hospital. He took a job in a private practice. <span class="green">CORRECT!</span></h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">Fixing the comma splice is as simple as replacing the comma with a period and capitalizing the first letter of our second clause. Instead of a compound sentence, we are left with two independent sentences.</p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The patient's diagnosis could not be confirmed, the doctor was still waiting on the test results. <span class="red">COMMA SPLICE!</span></h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This example is very similar to the last one. We are given two independent clauses, combined using only a comma. The comma splice is such a common error because it is so subtle. Sentences with comma splices don't always sound wrong to the ear, so they can be easy to miss when proofreading.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The patient's diagnosis could not be confirmed. The doctor was still waiting on the test results. <span class="green">CORRECT!</span></h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">Once again we correct our comma splice by dividing our independent clauses into two seperate sentences. Notice that the sentence still sounds similar when read aloud. Comma splices can be tricky!</p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>

