<h1>Example 2</h1>

<section>
	<p class="example-intro">The next way to correct a comma splice is by adding a <b>coordinating conjunction</b>. Coordinating conjunctions include and, but, for, or, nor, yet, and so. You should be able to identify these words and recognize when they are being used to connect to main clauses. Using a coordinating conjunction without a comma will result in a run-on sentence.</p>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The patient's family was present and supportive for every step of treatment, the doctor felt confident in their ability to provide home care. <span class="red">COMMA SPLICE!</span></h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">Once again we have a comma splice, as two independent clauses are joined with only a comma. Our independent clauses are "The patient's family was present and supportive for every step of treatment" and "the doctor felt confident in their ability to provide home care". We'll fix this one by adding a coordinating conjunction.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The patient's family was present and supportive for every step of treatment, so the doctor felt confident in their ability to provide home care. <span class="green">CORRECT!</span></h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">This example uses the coordinating conjunction "so" to fix the comma splice, successfully creating a compound sentence out of the two independent clauses.</p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The patient with diabetes needs to monitor their blood glucose level carefully, insulin treatment can be used to help maintain a healthy level. <span class="red">COMMA SPLICE!</span></h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">Again, this example follows the same pattern as the one above. It combines two independent clauses with a comma, leaving out the neccessary coordinating conjunction.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The patient with diabetes needs to monitor their blood glucose level carefully,<span class="green">CORRECT!</span></h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation"></p>
