<h1>Example 3</h1>

<section>
	<p class="example-intro">The last way to correct comma splices that we will use is to add a <b>subordinating conjunction</b> to one of our clauses. Subordinating clauses are words such as after, although, unless, when, and while. Whereas coordinating conjunctions combine two main clauses, subordinating conjunctions, as their name implies, subordinate one phrase to the other.</p>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The doctor came into the room and greeted the patient, he checked the patient's charts. <span class="red">COMMA SPLICE!</span></h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This example is a more obvious comma splice to the ear. This time we will fix it through the use of a subordinating conjunction.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">After the doctor came into the room and greeted the patient, he checked the patient's charts. <span class="green">CORRECT!</span></h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">Adding the subordinating conjunction, "after", to our first clause subordinates it to the second, correcting the comma splice.</p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The nurse recorded the patient's vital signs, the doctor conducted the interview. <span class="red">COMMA SPLICE!</span></h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">Again we see two independent clauses incorrectly joined with only a comma. Notice the way this example feels like a list cut short. We will fix it through the use of a subordinating conjunction.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The nurse recorded the patient's vital signs while the doctor conducted the interview.<span class="green">CORRECT!</span></h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">We've corrected the comma splice by removing the comma and adding the subordinating conjunction, while. When the subordinated clause comes after it's parent clause, there is no need for a comma. When the subordinated clause comes first, a comma is necessary.</p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>


